SIMPLE: instance
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Instance
<hw>In"stance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>instance</ets>, L. <ets>instantia</ets>, fr. <ets>instans</ets>.
See <er>Instant</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or quality of being instant or pressing;
urgency; solicitation; application; suggestion; motion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Undertook at her <qex>instance</qex> to restore them.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is instant or urgent; motive.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>instances</qex> that second marriage move⟦br⟧
Are base respects of thrift, but none of love.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Occasion; order of occurrence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These seem as if, in the time of Edward I., they were drawn up
into the form of a law, in the first <qex>instance</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which offers itself or is offered as an
illustrative case; something cited in proof or exemplification; a case
occurring; an example; <as>as, we could find no <ex>instance</ex> of
poisoning in the town within the past year</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Most remarkable <qex>instances</qex> of suffering.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A token; a sign; a symptom or indication.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Causes of instance</b></col>, <cd>those which proceed at
the solicitation of some party.</cd> <au>Hallifax.</au> -- <col><b>Court
of first instance</b></col>, <cd>the court by which a case is first
tried.</cd> -- <col><b>For instance</b></col>, <cd>by way of example or
illustration; for example.</cd> -- <col><b>Instance Court</b></col>
<fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>the Court of Admiralty acting within its ordinary
jurisdiction, as distinguished from its action as a <xex>prize
court</xex>.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Example; case. See <er>Example</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Instance
<hw>In"stance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Instanced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Instancing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To
mention as a case or example; to refer to; to cite; <as>as, to
<ex>instance</ex> a fact</as>.</def> <rj><au>H. Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I shall not <qex>instance</qex> an abstruse author.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Instance
<hw>In"stance</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To give an example.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This story doth not only <qex>instance</qex> in kingdoms, but in
families too.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instancy</ent>⟦br⟧
